  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

Selected data set was downloaded from Gapminder website - http://www.gapminder.org/. It is comprised of four excel spreadsheets of car_RTI_age_indicator, alcohol_consumption_indicator, tobacco_consumption_indicator, total_fertility_rate_indicator. In order to build the bubble scatter plots addiional data on GDP per capita was downloaded.

The data downloaded was then used to answer the questions such as:

1) What countries that have the lowest/highest GDP have lowest/highest average fertility level? How does it correspond to acohol or tobacco consumption data? Is this affected by GDP?

2) What countries that have the lowest/highest GDP have lowest/highest car crash statistics? How does it correspond to acohol or tobacco consumption data? Is this affected by GDP?

3) What countries that have the lowest/highest GDP have lowest/highest alco/tobacco consumption and is there any correlation between high/low alcohol and tobacco consumption?

Data Cleaning Process - Car mortality data¶

Since the data sheets were not consistent with years and the set of countries they were filtered from 1995 to 2008 years. In addition lots of data fields were N/A and they were dropped.

This data cleaning resulted in list of 95 conries for 2007 for 2005 for tobacco, alco consuption, fertility, gdp levels, and ranging numbers of contries for car_crash_indicator (from 7 to 69 in selected contries)

The column names were also cleaned, as well as Average, Min and Max values were calculated in order to make an easier visualization after.

In this cell I have renamed contry field from car crash data, droped values older then 1995, calculated Mean, Min and Max for each contry, then added the index '_car' to each of resulting columns.

In [13]:
# rename contry column from car crash data
car_age.rename(columns={'Car mortality per 100,000, age adjusted': 'cntry'}, inplace=True)

# drop values older then 1995
car_age=car_age.drop (car_age.loc[:,'1985':'1994'], 1)

# calculates Mean, Min and Max for each contry
car_age['Average']=car_age.loc[:, :].mean(axis=1)
car_age['Minimum']=car_age.loc[:,:].min(axis=1)
car_age['Maximum']=car_age.loc[:,:].max(axis=1)

#add the index '_car' to each of resulting columns
car_age.rename(columns=lambda x: x[:10] + "_car", inplace=True)

# rename contry column from car crash data
car_age.rename(columns={'cntry_car': 'cntry'}, inplace=True)

#double check the result

#Use data from .describe to fill the bin edges and assign bin names
bin_edges = [281.90, 1745.39, 5623.52, 16148.21, 95877.65] 
bin_names = [1,2,3,4]

#Function that will take the gdp value from each contry on a studied 
# time frame and convert it to GDP level according to bin edges
def categorize (column):
    return pd.cut(column, bin_edges, labels=bin_names)

# aply above function
gdp_cap=gdp_cap.loc[:,'1995':].apply(categorize,axis=1 )

# Reset index to see the cntry column 
gdp_cap=gdp_cap.reset_index()

#add the index '_gdp' to each of resulting columns
gdp_cap.rename(columns=lambda x: x[:10] + "_gdp", inplace=True)

# rename contry field to cntry
gdp_cap.rename(columns={'cntry_gdp': 'cntry'}, inplace=True)

# Drop all contries that hasn't got any data 
gdp_cap=gdp_cap.dropna(axis=0, how ='any')

# Check result
gdp_cap.info()

Data Cleaning Process - Inner merge¶

In this cell i tried to make an inner merge to filter out all the contries that are present in all five data sets

In [24]:
#perform inner merge between car mortality and alcohol consumption
merged_inner1 = pd.merge(car_age, alc_csn, on='cntry')

#perform inner merge merged car mortality, alcohol consumption, and fertility
merged_inner2 = pd.merge(merged_inner1, tot_fert,on='cntry')

#perform inner merge merged car mortality, alcohol consumption, fertility, and tobacco consumption
merged_inner3 = pd.merge(merged_inner2, tbc_csn,on='cntry')

#perform inner merge merged car mortality, alcohol consumption, fertility, tobacco consumption, 
#and GDP levels to make a finalised data set
merged_inner = pd.merge(merged_inner3, gdp_cap,on='cntry')

1) What countries that have the lowest/highest GDP have lowest/highest average fertility level? How does it correspond to acohol or tobacco consumption data? Is this affected by GDP?¶

Now, when we had acquainted with all variables it would be nice to add another one - The GDP levels. In order to accomplish this we need to create a colorful bubble plot that will have spheres colored and sized ranging with the GDP level.

In order to answer that we should build the bubble plot to see the contries with lowest/highest GDP as bubbles. The size is dependant on the level of GDP defined in previous section.

NOTE:

  • Fertility rate is measured as children per women

  • Alcohol consumption is measured as consumption per adult in liters

  • Tobacco consumption is measured as prevalence of current tobacco use among adults (%) both sexes

  • Car crash statistics is measured as Car road traffic mortality, age adjusted, per 100 000

First we define colors.

In [36]:
## Each number is taken from Average GDP column and then turned to color code respectively
colors = {1:'red', 2:'olive', 3:'blue', 4:'green'} 

#populates color codes according to GDP levels
ca=merged_inner['Average_gdp'].apply(lambda x: colors[x])

Then we need to create sub categories based on GDP levels which will be used as s parameter in bubble plots.

In [37]:
#Takes contries with GDP level 1 and assigns color from colors dict 
cond1 = merged_inner.loc[merged_inner['Average_gdp'] == 1]## Contries with lowest GDP
ca1=cond1['Average_gdp'].apply(lambda x: colors[x])

#Takes contries with GDP level 2 and assigns color from colors dict 
cond2 = merged_inner.loc[merged_inner['Average_gdp'] == 2]
ca2=cond2['Average_gdp'].apply(lambda x: colors[x])

#Takes contries with GDP level 3 and assigns color from colors dict 
cond3 = merged_inner.loc[merged_inner['Average_gdp'] == 3]
ca3=cond3['Average_gdp'].apply(lambda x: colors[x])

#Takes contries with GDP level 4 and assigns color from colors dict 
cond4 = merged_inner.loc[merged_inner['Average_gdp'] == 4]## Contries with highest GDP
ca4=cond4['Average_gdp'].apply(lambda x: colors[x])

AVERAGE VALUES fertility vs alcohol consumption¶

Ok, lets get it started with plotting the average values for all contries in our list with annotations as bubble plots.

colors = {1:'red', 2:'olive', 3:'blue', 4:'green'}

The whole data set is chosen to be shown as a bubble plot as it gives the most sense of data distribution where we can see relation between three variables.

In [38]:
# Creates a scatter plot that uses GDP levels to set colors and bubble sizes
ax=merged_inner.plot.scatter(x='Average_fert',y= 'Average_alc', c=ca,s = merged_inner['Average_gdp']*500,
                             alpha=0.4,figsize=(15,15),fontsize=15,label ='GDP', title='Fertility vs. alcohol consumption')

## Creates annotation for each contry
for i, txt in enumerate(merged_inner.cntry): 
    ax.annotate(txt, (merged_inner['Average_fert'].iat[i],merged_inner['Average_alc'].iat[i]),fontsize=8 )
    
# Creates legend
ax.legend(scatterpoints=2,loc='right',ncol=1,markerscale=1.5,fontsize=15)

#Sets x and y axes labels
ax.set_xlabel('Average_fert',fontsize = 15) #xlabel
ax.set_ylabel('Average_alc', fontsize = 15)#ylabel

#Sets x and y axes limits
ax.set_ylim(0,22)
ax.set_xlim(1,8);

This plot shows the destribution of data across the whole contry list with all the GDP. Here we can see that:

  • The lowest GDP county with highest fertility - Uganda and lowest fertility is in Kyrgystan.

  • The highest GDP contry with highest fertility - Israel and lowest fertility are Slovenia, Italy and Spain

  • The data investigation revieled that the most alcohol consumption is concentrated in contries with the higher income (levels 2,3 and 4). In addition these contries tend to have lower fertility levels.

Combined bubble plot looks a bit messy, so I've desided to plot the GDP levels contries separately. This is GDP level 1

Conclusions¶

1) What countries that have the lowest/highest GDP have lowest/highest average fertility level? How does it correspond to acohol or tobacco consumption data? Is this affected by GDP?¶

  • The lowest GDP county with highest fertility - Uganda and lowest fertility is in Kyrgystan.

  • The highest GDP contry with highest fertility - Israel and lowest fertility are Slovenia, Italy and Spain

  • The data investigation revieled that the most tobacco and alcohol consumption is concentrated in contries with the higher income (levels 2,3 and 4). In addition these contries tend to have lower fertility levels.

2) What countries that have the lowest/highest GDP have lowest/highest car crash statistics? How does it correspond to acohol or tobacco consumption data? Is this affected by GDP?¶

  • The lowest GDP county with highest car mortality - Comoros and lowest car mortality is in Combodia.

  • The highest GDP contry with highest car mortality - United Arab Emirates and lowest car mortality is in Malta

  • The data investigation revieled that the most tobacco and alcohol consumption is concentrated in contries with the higher income (levels 2,3 and 4). The most car mortality levels seem to be also spread across these contries .

3) What countries that have the lowest/highest GDP have lowest/highest alco/tobacco consumption and is there any correlation between high/low alcohol and tobacco consumption?¶

  • The lowest GDP county with highest alcohol consumption - Uganda and lowest in Bangladesh.

  • The highest GDP contry with highest alcohol consumption - Hungary and lowest is United Arab Emirates

  • The lowest GDP county with highest tobacco consumption - Bangladesh and lowestis in Ethiopia.

  • The highest GDP contry with highest tobacco consumption - Ethiopia and lowest is in Barbados

  • Most of tobacco and alcohol consumption is concentrated in contries with higher GDP (levels 2,3 and 4)

Potential drawbacks and improvements¶

  • As was stated earlier all the N/A value were droped to make the data list as consistent as possible, though these values impose significant gap in the reserch data that can be adjusted with more data available. The potential improvement could be filling the missing data at least with average values without the time frame.

  • The implementation of code in this report could be improved by inserting a function that will increase the speed of the bubble plot creation and reduce repetative code.

  • Analysis provided in this report could be easily questioned due to abscense of most of the data (as we had more then 200 contries and ended up with only 95 for four indicators. The car crash data even had less reading available, that were spread accross the data set.

  • The conclusions could be pumped up by inserting a descriptive statistical analysis. Calculating the Gaussian distribution tails could give more presize data on the end points.
